
[1]invent

   INVENT', v.t. [L. invenio, inventum; in and venio, to come; literally,
   to come to, to fall on, to meet, Eng. to find.]

   1. To find out something new; to devise something not before known; to
   contrive and produce something that did not before exist; as, to invent
   a new instrument of music; to invent a machine for spinning; to invent
   gunpowder. [See Invention.]

   2. To forge; to fabricate; to contrive falsely; as, to invent
   falsehoods.

   3. To feign; to frame by the imagination; as, to invent the machinery
   of a poem.

   4. To light on; to meet with. [This is the literal sense, but not now
   used.]
